>
  <h2>The problem</h2>
  <p>AI agents need API keys to call services. If those keys appear in the LLM's context window, they can leak — through model outputs, through logging, through prompt injection attacks. Storing keys in environment variables or <code>.env</code> files means any agent with shell access can read them.</p>

  <h2>How ostk handles secrets</h2>
  <p>Secrets are stored in your platform's native keychain (macOS Keychain, Linux secret service). The OS resolves them at runtime and injects them into tool calls. The key value never enters the LLM context window.</p>

  <pre><code># Store a key in the platform keychain
ostk secret set ANTHROPIC_API_KEY

# List available secrets
ostk secret list

# Retrieve to stdout (for debugging)
ostk secret get ANTHROPIC_API_KEY

# Print as export statement
ostk secret env ANTHROPIC_API_KEY</code></pre>

  <h2>Dual-gate authorization</h2>
  <p>A secret requires two things to be available to an agent:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>The key must exist in your platform keychain</li>
    <li>The key must be listed in your HUMANFILE's SECRET block</li>
  </ol>
  <p>Both gates must pass. A key in the keychain but not in the HUMANFILE is inaccessible. A key listed in the HUMANFILE but not in the keychain fails resolution.</p>

  <h2>Automatic provider mapping</h2>
  <p>When an agent's model requires an API key, the OS resolves it automatically. <code>claude-*</code> models map to <code>ANTHROPIC_API_KEY</code>. <code>gemini-*</code> maps to <code>GOOGLE_API_KEY</code>. No configuration needed for standard providers.</p>

  <h2>What gets masked</h2>
  <p>If a secret value appears anywhere in tool output, the OS masks it before it reaches the LLM. The mask preserves structure (prefix and length are visible) but hides the value. This catches leak vectors that environment variable approaches miss — like an agent running <code>env</code> or <code>printenv</code>.</p>
</FeaturePage>
